HEADWORD: Centrepiece
<hw>Cen"tre*piece`</hw> }</mhw>
<pr>(s⟦ecr⟧n"t⟦etil⟧r*p⟦emac⟧s`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An
ornament to be placed in the center, as of a table, ceiling, etc.; a
central article or figure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Specifically:</specif> <def>An arrangement of
flowers placed in the center of a table as an ornament while
dining.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The central or most important feature of an
activity, plan, or object; <as>as, the <ex>centerpiece</ex> of her
campaign was a proposal to slash taxes</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Centre punch</ent>⟦br⟧
